    <item>
      <title>I Built a FreeBSD Cloud to Use with FreeBSD</title>
      <link>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/i-built-a-freebsd-cloud-to-use-with-freebsd/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 22 Jul 2026 09:00:00 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/i-built-a-freebsd-cloud-to-use-with-freebsd/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;At the moment, I’m working on my own window manager for FreeBSD, called Asterwm. The goal is to make its UX similar to macOS, so I can switch from Mac to FreeBSD during the day without having to readjust my muscle memory.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;asterwm-for-freebsd.jpg&#34;&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/i-built-a-freebsd-cloud-to-use-with-freebsd/asterwm-for-freebsd_hu_53d63bbdc0695de7.webp&#34;  alt=&#34;User interface for Asterwm&#34;  width=&#34;1920&#34; height=&#34;1200&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; decoding=&#34;async&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;asterwm-for-freebsd-2.png&#34;&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/i-built-a-freebsd-cloud-to-use-with-freebsd/asterwm-for-freebsd-2.png&#34; alt=&#34;User interface for Asterwm&#34; &#xA;  width=&#34;1919&#34; height=&#34;1199&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; decoding=&#34;async&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;One of the most important things for me was being able to access both my work and personal files.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I know I could install ready-to-use software for Google Drive or something similar. But I decided to use the power of Codex to build my own cloud solution instead.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>The FreeBSD Music Collection</title>
      <link>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/freebsd-music-collection/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 01 Jul 2026 09:00:00 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/freebsd-music-collection/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/freebsd-music-collection/images/freebsd-music-collection-masks_hu_73adbd170058215a.webp&#34;  srcset=&#34;https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/freebsd-music-collection/images/freebsd-music-collection-masks_hu_ed785b4cee8b273b.webp 480w , https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/freebsd-music-collection/images/freebsd-music-collection-masks_hu_f496629bda3b423d.webp 768w , https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/freebsd-music-collection/images/freebsd-music-collection-masks_hu_1d606202074fb489.webp 1536w , https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/freebsd-music-collection/images/freebsd-music-collection-masks_hu_73adbd170058215a.webp 1660w&#34;&#xA;  sizes=&#34;(min-width: 768px) 768px, calc(100vw - 2rem)&#34;  alt=&#34;Group of people holding FreeBSD daemon masks in an urban city setting&#34;  width=&#34;1660&#34; height=&#34;947&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; decoding=&#34;async&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This is my FreeBSD music collection. It consists of songs inspired by FreeBSD releases, experiments, and desktop and server experiences that have become part of everyday life. It was built using Suno AI and then tweaked and polished each one.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;freebsd-from-14-to-15-song&#34;&gt;&amp;ldquo;FreeBSD From 14 to 15&amp;rdquo; Song&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Context: I recently upgraded my server from FreeBSD 14 to 15.1-RELEASE-p1, which went smoothly. To make the song I used old melody that I had before, modified it 19 times in Suno to tweak the voice, melody, rhythm, lyrics, and voice accents. Then, I polished it in Ableton Live 12 and combined the best parts of different tracks and lyrics into one song.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to Fit the FreeBSD Logo in a Perfect Circle</title>
      <link>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/how-to-fit-the-freebsd-logo-in-a-perfect-circle/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 27 May 2026 12:00:00 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/how-to-fit-the-freebsd-logo-in-a-perfect-circle/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The FreeBSD and Apple logos are quite similar. &lt;br/&gt;&#xA;Both have a heavy base and leaves / tails on top.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/how-to-fit-the-freebsd-logo-in-a-perfect-circle/apple-freebsd-wrong-circle-fit.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Apple and FreeBSD logos compared by their heavy base and top detail, followed by a wrong circular crop approach&#34; &#xA;  width=&#34;928&#34; height=&#34;200&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; decoding=&#34;async&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;this-is-how-apple-fits-its-logo-into-a-circle&#34;&gt;This is how Apple fits its logo into a circle&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/how-to-fit-the-freebsd-logo-in-a-perfect-circle/apple-homepod-logo.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Apple logo centered on the circular top surface of a black HomePod&#34; &#xA;  width=&#34;1472&#34; height=&#34;980&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; decoding=&#34;async&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;With guides:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/how-to-fit-the-freebsd-logo-in-a-perfect-circle/apple-homepod-circle-guides.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Apple HomePod top with orange circular guides around the speaker surface and Apple logo&#34; &#xA;  width=&#34;1472&#34; height=&#34;980&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; decoding=&#34;async&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>I Connected a Desktop Phone to a FreeBSD Server, so Now I Can Call It</title>
      <link>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/desktop-phone-connected-to-freebsd-server/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 14 Apr 2026 09:00:00 -0400</pubDate>
      <guid>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/desktop-phone-connected-to-freebsd-server/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I turned a Panasonic KX-T2315 desk phone into a physical menu for my FreeBSD server. When I pick up the handset, the phone adapter calls Asterisk, waits for one digit, and triggers a predefined script on the FreeBSD server. This post covers the phone restoration, HT801 setup, Asterisk configuration, Lua dialplan, Python AGI dispatcher, and the full config download.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The basic flow looks like this:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#abb2bf;background-color:#282c34;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-sh&#34; data-lang=&#34;sh&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;Panasonic KX-T2315 analog phone&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;|&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;| FXS phone cable&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;v&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;Grandstream HT801&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;|&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;| SIP + RTP&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;v&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;FreeBSD &lt;span style=&#34;color:#d19a66&#34;&gt;14&lt;/span&gt; + Asterisk&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;|&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;| AGI&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;v&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;Python dispatcher&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;|&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#x9;&#x9;v&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;Predefined server-side scripts&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/desktop-phone-connected-to-freebsd-server/images/Panasonic-KX-T2315-connected-to-FreeBSD-schema_hu_34bbf5bf19287670.webp&#34;  srcset=&#34;https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2026/desktop-phone-connected-to-freebsd-server/images/Panasonic-KX-T2315-connected-to-FreeBSD-schema_hu_34bbf5bf19287670.webp 2400w&#34;&#xA;  sizes=&#34;(min-width: 768px) 768px, calc(100vw - 2rem)&#34;  alt=&#34;&#34;  width=&#34;2400&#34; height=&#34;1200&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; decoding=&#34;async&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to Match FreeBSD’s YouTube Seeking Speed on macOS</title>
      <link>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/how-i-match-freebsd-youtube-speed-on-macos/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 25 Nov 2025 12:55:15 +0100</pubDate>
      <guid>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/how-i-match-freebsd-youtube-speed-on-macos/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;On FreeBSD, YouTube seeking feels instant: click anywhere on the seek bar and playback resumes immediately. On macOS, Firefox gave me a short pause after each seek.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The fix that worked for me was &lt;strong&gt;not&lt;/strong&gt; global macOS TCP tuning. Those system-wide tweaks can affect other apps. The stable solution was Firefox-only: keep HTTP/3/QUIC enabled, give Firefox a much larger media cache, reduce media throttling, and prefer the faster MP4/H.264 path over AV1/WebM MSE.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>MATE on FreeBSD: macOS-Like Setup Guide: Font Rendering, UI Tweaks, and Settings</title>
      <link>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/mate-on-freebsd-macos-like-setup-guide-font-rendering-ui-tweaks-and-settings/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 23 May 2025 20:38:13 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/mate-on-freebsd-macos-like-setup-guide-font-rendering-ui-tweaks-and-settings/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fonts&#34;&gt;Font rendering settings&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;#keyboard_and_mouse&#34;&gt;Keyboard and mouse settings&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;#interface&#34;&gt;Interface settings&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;#tearing&#34;&gt;Turn on TearFree&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;#wallpapers&#34;&gt;Wallpapers&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;#mate_theme&#34;&gt;macOS theme for Mate&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;#mate_spotlight&#34;&gt;Spotlight replacement&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;As I mentioned earlier, I noticed similarities between FreeBSD and macOS—after 20 years of using macOS, returning to FreeBSD feels like coming home. But I don’t like the font rendering used in non-macOS systems. Partly because Apple did it very well — &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.typeroom.eu/steve-jobs-calligraphy-apple-typography-legacy&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;nofollow&#34;&gt;Steve Jobs had a great understanding of typography&lt;/a&gt; — and partly because I’m just used to it.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to Install the FreeBSD AMDGPU Driver on a Beelink SER5 5560U</title>
      <link>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/how-to-install-freebsd-amdgpu-driver-beelink-ser5-5560u/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 22 May 2025 22:45:11 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/how-to-install-freebsd-amdgpu-driver-beelink-ser5-5560u/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;After installing FreeBSD 14.2 fresh on my Beelink SER5 5560U, I installed the GPU driver and enabled the TearFree option for better desktop usage by following these steps:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/how-to-install-freebsd-amdgpu-driver-beelink-ser5-5560u/Beelink-SER5-5560U.webp&#34; alt=&#34;&#34; &#xA;  width=&#34;2000&#34; height=&#34;1174&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; decoding=&#34;async&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;1-speed-up-keyboard-repeat-rate&#34;&gt;1. Speed Up Keyboard Repeat Rate&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#abb2bf;background-color:#282c34;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-sh&#34; data-lang=&#34;sh&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#7f848e&#34;&gt;# kbdcontrol -r fast&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Edit &lt;code&gt;/etc/rc.conf&lt;/code&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#abb2bf;background-color:#282c34;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-sh&#34; data-lang=&#34;sh&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#e06c75&#34;&gt;keyrate&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#56b6c2&#34;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#98c379&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;fast&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h3 id=&#34;2-install-xorg&#34;&gt;2. Install Xorg&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#abb2bf;background-color:#282c34;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-sh&#34; data-lang=&#34;sh&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#7f848e&#34;&gt;# pkg install -y xorg&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h3 id=&#34;3-add-user-to-necessary-groups&#34;&gt;3. Add User to Necessary Groups&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#abb2bf;background-color:#282c34;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-sh&#34; data-lang=&#34;sh&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#7f848e&#34;&gt;# pw groupmod video -m username&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#7f848e&#34;&gt;# pw groupmod wheel -m username&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Verify with:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Comparing Performance of MacBook Pro M1 Pro to Mini PC on FreeBSD</title>
      <link>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/freebsd-vs-macos-for-daily-use-my-personal-migration-story/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 19 May 2025 22:15:36 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/freebsd-vs-macos-for-daily-use-my-personal-migration-story/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;As a designer I&amp;rsquo;ve been using macOS since 2005, but with each new update, I dislike the direction Apple is heading in. They add unnecessary features that use system resources and can&amp;rsquo;t be disabled. My seven-year-old MacBook Pro with an Intel processor became so slow and unresponsive with the latest macOS version that I can&amp;rsquo;t use it at all anymore. If your Mac can&amp;rsquo;t handle the latest macOS version, the only solution is to buy a more powerful Mac. This is probably fine, people upgrade their hardware from time to time, and this is part of the evolution of the field. However, Apple can deem any five-year-old Mac obsolete. It seems like they have more control over your computer than you do.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Can Cheap MiniPC with FreeBSD 14 Outperform MacBook Pro M1 Pro?</title>
      <link>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/can-cheap-minipc-with-freebsd-14-outperform-macbook-pro-m1-pro/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 05 Feb 2025 22:25:51 +0100</pubDate>
      <guid>https://interfacecraft.online/blog/2025/can-cheap-minipc-with-freebsd-14-outperform-macbook-pro-m1-pro/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h3 id=&#34;tldr&#34;&gt;TL;DR&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I put my €1800 MacBook Pro M1 Pro head-to-head with a €300 mini PC and found the cheaper option surprisingly fast. While the mini PC couldn&amp;rsquo;t completely replace my Mac for work due to some software and hardware limitations, it made me question the need for expensive purchases. Do we really need the latest and greatest hardware to be productive? Or are we being pushed to constantly upgrade for features we might not even fully utilize?&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
